ic Science on Trial</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Report of the House of Commons Science and Technolog</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">y Committee (2004-05) HC 96-I, 173</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Above n.1, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">9.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> The Admissibility of Expert Evidence in Criminal Proceedings in England and Wales.  A New Approach to the Determination of Evidentiary Reliability.  A Consultation Paper.  Consultation Paper No 190. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Expert Evidence in criminal Proceedings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Law Com</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> No 325,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> 1.2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn10"></a><a href="#_ftnref10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Ibid.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn11"></a><a href="#_ftnref11">[11]</a><span s